## Part 1. **Network Architecture:** In this lab we designed and implemented a segmented enterprise network that included IT, OT, Remote Station, and a DMZ environment. 
[Network Topology Link Here]
**Physical Layer (Layer 1)** Physical cabling represents Layer 1 (the Physical Layer) of the OSI model because it constitutes the tangible, hardware-based 
infrastructure responsible for transmitting raw bits (0s and 1s) as electrical, optical, or radio signals. It is the foundation for all network 
communication, defining the physical connectors, cable types, and voltage levels used to transport data.

**Data Link Layer (Layer 2)** Layer 2 switches operate at the Data Link layer by utilizing MAC addresses to direct network traffic specifically to the intended 
destination device, rather than broadcasting it to everyone. They build a MAC address table by observing the source address of incoming frames, 
allowing them to map specific MAC addresses to physical switch ports and forward data only to the relevant port, reducing network congestion.

**Network Layer (Layer 3)**  IP addressing and routing are Layer 3 (Network Layer) functionalities because they manage logical, hierarchical addressing to 
route data across different, interconnected networks, rather than just delivering data within a single local segment. Layer 3 handles the 
logical addressing (IP addresses) and path selection (routing) needed for global communication.

