## 💡 Reflection
This lab demonstrated the interdependence of network architecture and security in enterprise environments. 
By creating and configuring a network that included IT, OT, remote, and DMZ environments, I had the opportunity to 
experiment with CISCO packet tracer, and understand ways to improve connectivity and security. 
By structuring the network into separate segments we could ensure that critical systems, 
especially those in the OT environment, are not directly exposed to external threats. 
Throughout the lab, I gained a deeper understanding of how the OSI model applies to real-world networking and security. 
Although I worked hard to ensure the Physical and Data Link layers had proper connectivity, I still had challenges designing
an appropriate way to fully connect the pump mechanism.  The Network layer would have allowed for communication between the 
different segments, had I been able to fully implement the Route path. Because I was not able to properly configure them, 
the routing also introduced security risks by allowing unauthorized access between networks. 
I learned that each layer should contribute to both communication and protection. By comparing HTTP and HTTPS, we could show
how encryption protects data from interception, while SSH demonstrated secure remote management compared to Telnet. 
Analyzing TCP and UDP helped us understand how reliability and visibility impact security monitoring. 
The shellshock vulnerability showed how unpatched systems can be attacked, especially when exposed to external 
networks like the DMZ. All of this reinforced the importance of regular updates, proper access control, and network 
segmentation. Although this was one of the most challenging labs I have completed so far, and my execution was not completely successful, 
it gave me hands-on experience in building and securing a network. Overall, this lab showed that effective security 
must be built into the network design itself. A well-structured architecture, combined with secure protocols and 
proper configuration, is essential for protecting enterprise systems and critical infrastructure from cyber threats.

